messages.content: You are tasked with creating a structured output from the provided user message.

Full HTTP request path
- /invoices/{id}

Reasoning summary
- The invoices routes are mounted under the prefix /invoices in index.js.
- In routes/invoices.js, the following route for a specific invoice id is defined:
  - GET /:id -> getInvoice
  - PATCH /:id -> updateInvoice
  - DELETE /:id -> deleteInvoice
- Therefore the full path for operations on a single invoice is /invoices/{id}.
- Other routes under /invoices include:
  - GET /count -> getTotalCount
  - GET / -> getInvoicesByUser
  - POST / -> createInvoice
- HEAD, OPTIONS, TRACE, PUT behavior is determined by code behavior and middleware:
  - HEAD is automatically handled by Express for GET routes.
  - OPTIONS is handled by the global CORS middleware.
  - TRACE is not implemented by this code.
  - PUT is not defined for /invoices/{id} (no PUT route exists here).
  - POST is not defined for /invoices/{id} (POST exists on /invoices/ but not on /invoices/{id}).

Endpoint method acceptability for /invoices/{id}
- All HTTP methods acceptable: false
- HEAD: true (Express provides HEAD support automatically for GET routes)
- POST: false (no POST route for /invoices/{id})
- OPTIONS: true (handled by CORS middleware)
- TRACE: false (not implemented in code)
- GET: true (GET /invoices/{id} exists)
- PUT: false (no PUT route for /invoices/{id})
- DELETE: true (DELETE /invoices/{id} exists)
- PATCH: true (PATCH /invoices/{id} exists)

Explanation
- The code defines the /invoices/{id} endpoints via router.get('/:id', ...), router.patch('/:id', ...), and router.delete('/:id', ...), which map to GET, PATCH, and DELETE for that path.
- HEAD is not explicitly defined but Express automatically handles HEAD requests for routes that have a GET handler, so HEAD is acceptable here.
- OPTIONS is supported through the global CORS middleware (cors()), so OPTIONS is acceptable.
- Other methods (PUT, POST) are not defined for /invoices/{id}, so they are not acceptable for this specific endpoint.
- TRACE is not implemented anywhere in the code, so it is not acceptable.
